</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="62D43E84809B8F34826DC4622B21E812" pageId="14" pageNumber="101" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="EFAC2F9C827E098D09A32AEA763D9061" pageId="14" pageNumber="101">
<taxonomicName id="13CF89866007A72443E5CF7F83DAE562" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Perdita (Cockerellia) imbellis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imbellis" subGenus="Cockerellia">Perdita (Cockerellia) imbellis</taxonomicName>
Timberlake, 1968: 21, ♂. Holotype male: USA, Arizona, Coconino Co., 28 May 1954, F. Werner [CAS type no. 13525]. Examined.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1AA1B8F3465179110E83AFDFE833BC16" pageId="14" pageNumber="101">
<taxonomicName id="A557B3FB25BB22FD349BC41BA52E2D7C" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Perdita (Cockerellia) hilaris" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hilaris" subGenus="Cockerellia">Perdita (Cockerellia) hilaris</taxonomicName>
Timberlake, 1968: 2, ♂ (syn. 
<bibRefCitation id="B008F12BF970442633A88AC329E0E55D" author="Timberlake, PH" journalOrPublisher="University of California Publications in Entomology" pageId="16" pageNumber="103" pagination="1 - 65" title="Supplementary studies on the systematics of the genus Perdita (Hymenoptera, Andrenidae). Part II." volume="85" year="1980">Timberlake 1980</bibRefCitation>
). Holotype male: USA, Utah, Dixie State Park, 13 June 1961, G.E. Bohart [CAS type no. 14554]. Not examined.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8F632A710E536D293AF28DF2AB4AC45A" pageId="14" pageNumber="101">
<taxonomicName id="F18BCEF386F9A3CBF9E50FE3017CB6E3" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Perdita (Procockerellia) brachyglossa" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brachyglossa" subGenus="Procockerellia">Perdita (Procockerellia) brachyglossa</taxonomicName>
Timberlake, 1971: 6, ♀. Holotype female: USA, Arizona, Coconino Co., Four and one-half miles southwest of Marble Canyon, 30 August 1967, P.H. Timberlake, on 
<taxonomicName id="F87309C2651D648256CC1D4ED9DAE250" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Andrenidae" genus="Thelesperma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Thelesperma" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="101" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Thelesperma</taxonomicName>
[CAS type no. 14448]. Examined. Syn. n.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F9DA02777310A3E113E56C59A9BCE999" pageId="14" pageNumber="101" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="49243C341E7033ACFF8DEC96F142C28F" pageId="14" pageNumber="101">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4AABE37E941826484D52691F0A593532" pageId="14" pageNumber="101">
<taxonomicName id="978E92EF570C4D85BB00A23B8C2BDA79" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Perdita (Procockerellia) brachyglossa" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brachyglossa" subGenus="Procockerellia">Perdita (Procockerellia) brachyglossa</taxonomicName>
was described from a single female specimen. 
<bibRefCitation id="C6E864E986F3252EEDAE1B41A8D89833" author="Timberlake, PH" journalOrPublisher="University of California Publications in Entomology" pageId="16" pageNumber="103" pagination="1 - 63" title="Supplementary studies on the systematics of the genus Perdita (Hymenoptera: Andrenidae)." volume="66" year="1971">Timberlake (1971)</bibRefCitation>
reported that the female had four maxillary palpi. Examination of the holotype revealed four maxillary palpi on one side and one palp on the other. In every morphological character except the palpi, the holotype of 
<taxonomicName id="3A20F918094D8F9F36243D2B3AB4F3CB" genus="P." lsidName="P. brachyglossa" pageId="14" pageNumber="101" rank="species" species="brachyglossa">P. brachyglossa</taxonomicName>
clearly matches 
<taxonomicName id="314ADBE9AFE573BE9824D21E5DD5E0B1" genus="P." lsidName="P. imbellis" pageId="14" pageNumber="101" rank="species" species="imbellis">P. imbellis</taxonomicName>
. It seems likely that the mouthparts of the holotype of 
<taxonomicName id="BF3F8E334D473961061C559248B4DA9D" genus="P." lsidName="P. brachyglossa" pageId="14" pageNumber="101" rank="species" species="brachyglossa">P. brachyglossa</taxonomicName>
are either damaged or aberrant.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FBA75DE9EFFB3B2881EC09B65B547DA0" pageId="14" pageNumber="101">
Due to a lapsus calami in 
<bibRefCitation id="AA4217AC6815564F67E08EBCA35CB463" author="Timberlake, PH" journalOrPublisher="University of California Publications in Entomology" pageId="16" pageNumber="103" pagination="1 - 65" title="Supplementary studies on the systematics of the genus Perdita (Hymenoptera, Andrenidae). Part II." volume="85" year="1980">Timberlake (1980)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName id="B4CC401971C548382217F63EBE393581" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Perdita albomaculata" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albomaculata">Perdita albomaculata</taxonomicName>
Timberlake, 1980, 
<taxonomicName id="3A3BD38F41990EA08D4AD6AECCE4BE8E" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Perdita imbellis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imbellis">Perdita imbellis</taxonomicName>
Timberlake, 1968, and 
<taxonomicName id="06824A82446F7E986D37362BE64B80EF" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Perdita luculenta" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luculenta">Perdita luculenta</taxonomicName>
Timberlake, 1968 were all referred to as being in subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="C006F7362691B3B2960FBFE55A7614EE" genus="Cockerellula" lsidName="Cockerellula" pageId="14" pageNumber="101" rank="genus">Cockerellula</taxonomicName>
Strand, 1932. They all belong in subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="9054B015653516CEEA1218A55CDC6C53" lsidName="(Cockerellia)" pageId="14" pageNumber="101" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Cockerellia">Cockerellia</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
